, Lancashire, England":"Wardley, Lancashire, England","Tyldesley, Lancashire, England":"Tyldesley, Lancashire, England"},"en":{"1330–22 March 1401":"1330–22 March 1401","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1340–1375":"1340–from9January1375to8January1376","1370–1434":"1370–1434","1372–1421":"1372–1421","1312–1366":"1312–1366","1315–1373":"1315–1373","22 March 1401":"22 March 1401","1330":"1330","1362":"1362","1373":"1373","1340":"1340","1372":"1372","1382":"1382","1370":"1370","1337":"1337","1315":"1315","1347":"1347","1434":"1434","1401":"1401","1312":"1312","1366":"1366","30 May 1372":"30 May 1372","1344":"1344","1421":"1421","1453":"1453","1375":"from 9 January 1375 to 8 January 1376","England":"England","Lancashire, England":"Lancashire, England","Worsley, Lancashire, England":"Worsley, Lancashire, England","Wardley, Lancashire, England":"Wardley, Lancashire, England","Tyldesley, Lancashire, England":"Tyldesley, Lancashire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Worsley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Lancashire): habitational name from Worsley in Lancashire or Worsley Farm in Rock (Worcestershire). The Lancashire placename may derive from an Old English personal name <i>Weorcgȳth</i> (genitive <i>Weorcgȳthes</i>) + Old English <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, woodland clearing’. The Worcestershire placename may take its name from a lost stream-name <i>Worf</i> + Old English <i>lēah</i>."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["Formed from Margaret."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705193,"age":7,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":52,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret Worsley was born in 1330, in Wardley, Lancashire, England, her father, Jordan de Worsley, was 18 and her mother, Margaret, was 16. She married Thurston de  Tyldesley in 1362, in Tyldesley, Lancashire, England. They were the parents of at least 2 sons. She died on 22 March 1401, in England, at the age of 71."},"et":{"1330–22 March 1401":"1330–22. märts 1401","1330–1401":"1330–1401","1340–1375":"1340–9.j